  "prompt": "What is the difference between norco and hydrocodone?",
  "response": "Norco and hydrocodone are closely related, but there are some key differences:\n\n1. Composition:\n- Hydrocodone is the primary opioid pain medication\n- Norco is a combination medication containing hydrocodone and acetaminophen\n\n2. Specifics:\n- Hydrocodone alone is a pure opioid pain reliever\n- Norco contains:\n  * 5-10 mg of hydrocodone\n  * 325 mg of acetaminophen\n\n3. Usage:\n- Hydrocodone can be prescribed alone or in combination\n- Norco is specifically used for moderate to severe pain management\n\n4. Side effects:\n- Both have similar opioid-related side effects\n- Norco has additional acetaminophen-related risks, such as potential liver damage\n\n5. Prescription:\n- Both require a prescription\n- Norco is typically more tightly controlled due to its combination of medications\n\n6. Function:\n- Hydrocodone provides pain relief\n- Norco provides pain relief with added fever reduction from acetaminophen\n\nWhile similar, Norco is a specific brand/formulation of a hydrocodone-containing medication.",
